title: For Sale/Trade:  Star PD 45
location: Clayton, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
The Star Model PD is a compact and lightweight semi-automatic pistol which was manufactured from 1975 to 1990 by the firearms manufacturing company Star Bonifacio Echeverria, S.A., located in the city of Eibar in the Basque region of Spain.

The Model PD can be loaded with six .45 ACP pistol cartridges in the detachable internal magazine, plus one in the chamber, and was very popular with police and civilian users in the self-defense and backup gun role, especially in the United States.

The Star PD improved on its predecessor (Star Model PKM) by using a low-profile adjustable rear sight and by removing material from the slide and other small changes. These modifications, combined with its aluminum alloy construction, resulted in a slim, compact, lightweight and relatively powerful pistol, revolutionary for the time. 

It comes with 2 extra buffers, a recoil spring not yet installed to reduce felt recoil. Original grips, case, extra 7 rnd mag. Nice lightweight, 25oz, package. Good carry gun. I have another. title: For Sale/Trade:  1 of 8000 Kokura arsenal type 97 Arisaka Japaneese sniper rifle
postcontent: I bet you don't have one of these!  Here is your chance to own a unique piece of WWII history.  This rifle was almost certainly smuggled home after capture by one of our fathers or grandfathers.   Because there were only 8000 of these ever made, one in perfect condition is worth $10,000 or more.  Since this is genuine history, it is not in perfect condition.  First off, there is no scope, and the scopes were numbered to the gun.  That being said, very few type 97s have scopes at all and only a handful have matching ones.  The mount on this gun is fine, so you could pick up a scope or replica at a gun show or ebay and mount it easily.  Next the stock has been "duffel cut", meaning the very front part of the stock has been cut off and the front most barrel band(a numbered part) is missing.  This is why the mum and all of the rest of the bluing is in excellent condition, our hero cut it down and stuffed it in his personal duffel rather than have it ground up and shipped home properly.  Finally the magazine floorplate is a mismatched number, this was common due to en mass cleaning  and practice sessions and probably happened before it ever saw service.  All of the rest of the numbered parts match and are in great condition, including the bolt shroud witch is often missing.  The rifling is not too bad, and it shoots just fine. I'll even throw in half a box of hornady 6.5 jap ammo.  Since this is not a perfect gun, its not worth 10,000.  But its also not a $300 Arisaka you find in pawn shops.  I think $1000 seems fair for a very rare piece of history that is in decent condition and functions just fine.  I would almost rather trade it though, so let me know what you have.  Face to face in WA state only!

title: For Sale:  M1A M14 National Match .308 1978 Pre Ban
location: Summerville Moncks Corner, Charleston, South Carolina
postcontent:
Springfield M1A Rifle with I've had this rifle in my collection for quite a while and I've shot it, cleaned it, shot t some more.  To be honest, it's boring to shoot.  It doesn't miss.  I purchased this from the original owner who bought it in 1978.  His son was on the Marine Corps rifle team at the time and this rifle made several trips to Camp Perry.  It came with a commercial barrel when new, but was later changed out by a Marine armorer in the summer of 84.  If you know m1a's, then the list below will mean something to you.

Barrel # 28REDACTED 9-83 82472 (USMC Med weight NM Broach cut rifling, 22")
Bolt  TRW
Rear sight NM2A
FT sight NM052
Op rod. H&R
Trigger is SA
Bedded stock (still in excellent condition) sans a few scratches from use and safe storage.

Basically the rifle made the trip to Camp Perry every couple of years and while there, the guys from Springfield and some service buddies made improvements.  I added the Springfield Government Model 6x40 scope with BDC reticle.  It is not zeroed to the rifle, as I had it on my other M1a the last time I went to the range.

This is not a safe queen, nor did it hang over the mantle.  It was shot, cleaned, shot some more and so on.  The rifling is superb and the best guess we have on round count is between 680 and 720 rds since 1984.  

  I prefer to sell locally, but will consider shipping to your ffl, but only after you understand what you are buying.  Prefer phone calls over email, as I'm not near the computer very often.  Please no picture collectors, I suck at taking pics and unless I think you might actually be a buyer, I won't be sending dozens of pics.  

This is an example of what an M1A is supposed to be.  Not a roll of the dice modern built NM that may or may not shoot sub moa.  This rifle is what you would expect it to be.  I don't have primo, pristine, never seen daylight weapons, I shoot my stuff.  I'm selling this to fund an expensive transferable I've got my eye on.  I won't be taking trades or low ball offers.  

Call 843-224-nine one 94
